%%TITLE
Markers of HPV infection and survival in patients with head and neck tumors.
%%ABSTRACT
The purpose of this study was to determine whether changes in human papillomavirus (HPV) DNA prevalence in oral rinses and/or HPV-specific antibody levels in the sera of patients with oral/oropharyngeal cancer have prognostic significance. One hundred and forty-two patients with oral/oropharyngeal tumors were enrolled. The presence of HPV DNA was assayed in tumor tissue and oral rinses and HPV-specific antibodies were assessed in the sera. Oral rinses were collected before treatment and one year after the treatment. Sera were drawn before treatment, one month, and one year after the end of the treatment. Altogether, 59.2% of tumors were HPV positive. The presence of HPV DNA in the tumors correlated with HPV DNA positivity in oral rinses and with HPV-specific antibodies in the sera. Out of 66 patients with HPV-positive oral rinses at enrolment, 84.8% became negative at one-year follow-up, while most patients remained seropositive for HPV-specific antigens. However, the mean titers of HPV16 E6 and/or E7 antibodies at follow-up were significantly lower. Of 16 patients with recurrences at follow-up (alive on second sampling), six were positive at enrolment for HPV16 E6 and/or E7 antibodies. In five of these, no decrease in antibody levels was observed. Titers of antibodies specific for HPV16 capsid antigens did not change during the follow-up. Our data suggest that the detection of antibodies specific for the HPV 16 E6 and E7 oncoproteins may serve not only as a marker of HPV etiology, but also as a marker of recurrence and a prognostic indicator in patients with HPV-positive tumors.
%%MATERIAL AND METHODS
Study Population
Patients with primary squamous cell cancer of the oral cavity or oropharynx (ICD-10:C01–C06, C9–10) treated in the Department of Otolaryngology and Head and Neck Surgery in 2001–2007 who agreed to sign the informed consent form were enrolled. The study received ofﬁcial institutional and ethical approval from the participating institutions. Data on demographics, general risk factors for SCCHN, and risks related to HPV exposure were collected by a questionnaire. A medical report form was completed for each patient at enrol- ment and at one month and one year follow-up examina- tions. The medical and pathology reports were completed for each patient. Altogether, 142 patients were included in the study. At enrolment, tumor tissue and blood samples were available from all patients and oral rinse was available from all but one subject.
Oral Rinses
Oral exfoliated cells were obtained by having patients rinse the mouth vigorously with a solution of 10 ml of phosphate buffered saline (PBS, pH 7.4; AccuGENE, Cambrex Bio Sci- ence, Verviers, Belgium) for 30 sec. The samples were centri- fuged for 7 min at 3,000 rpm, the pellet was washed twice, consecutively with 30 and 10 ml of PBS, and the cells were resuspended in 5 ml of PBS. The numbers of squamous and basal cells per 1 ml of suspension were determined in a hemocytometer. The cells were aliquoted and frozen at
270oC. DNA for HPV detection was extracted from a mini- mum of 250,000 cells using Puregene Core Kit A (Gentra Qiagen, Hilden, Germany), according to the manufacturer’s protocol. The eluted DNA was precipitated and dissolved in 10 mM Tris-Cl, pH 8.0, in the volume, which corresponded to 7,500 cells/ml.
Tumor Specimens
All but three patients underwent surgery and cancer tissue taken during the procedure was sent on dry ice to the pathol- ogy department. In three patients who were not treated by surgery, biopsy specimens were available for evaluation of HPV. The pathologist obtained two side-by-side sections of the tumor from the primary site. One of the paired sections from each anatomical site was then labeled, snap frozen in liquid nitrogen, and stored for future analysis. Each remain- ing paired section was ﬁxed in neutral formalin and parafﬁn embedded. From each parafﬁn block, the ﬁrst and the last sections were histologically analyzed to conﬁrm that the sec- tions in between—assigned for the detection of viral nucleic acids and immunohistochemical analysis—contained at least 10% of tumor cells in the entire volume of the sample.
Total nucleic acids were extracted from two 20 mm sec-
tions. In 62 samples, only DNA extraction was performed by a proteinase K method as described previously.23 The remaining 80 samples were suitable for simultaneous extrac- tion of DNA and RNA by means of the Ambion Recover- AllTM Total Nucleic Acid Isolation Kit for FFPE Tissues (Applied Bioscience, Austin, TX). Care was taken to avoid sample cross-contamination.
PCR
As an internal control, a 110 bp fragment of the human beta- globin gene was ampliﬁed as described previously to check the integrity of DNA and the absence of PCR inhibitors.23
HPV DNA detection was performed by PCR with primers speciﬁc for the L1 region (GP51/GP61) as described previ- ously24 and HPV typing was done by reverse line blot hybridization with probes speciﬁc for 37 types as speciﬁed in detail by van den Brule et al.25 Futhermore, MY09/11 pri- mers were used for a standard PCR assay followed by sequencing.26
Samples positive by MY09/11 PCR, as well as those sam- ples which did not hybridize on RLB but which revealed a clear band on an agarose gel, were subjected to DNA
Int. J. Cancer: 133, 1832–1839 (2013) VC 2013 UICC
nucleotide sequencing to determine the exact HPV geno- type.24 Detected HPV types were classiﬁed according to de Villiers et al.27 in the family Papillomaviridae genus Alphapa- pillomavirus, which contains mucosal types and genus Beta- papillomavirus types, which mostly infect skin tissue. The classiﬁcation of mucosal HPV types into HR and low-risk (LR) types was done according to Munoz et al.28
Serological Assays
Five milliliters of blood were collected from each subject en- rolled. Serum was separated by centrifugation at 3000 rpm for 10 min, aliquoted and stored at 220oC.
The presence of IgG antibodies to antigens derived from HPV-speciﬁc proteins was tested as described elsewhere.12 In brief, the enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA) was used. The virus-speciﬁc antigens were virus-like particles (VLP), based on the L1 recombinant proteins, mimicking HPV 16, 18, 31, and 33 capsids and HPV 16 E6 and E7 on- coproteins. Empty shells—VLP—were prepared in the recombinant baculovirus system (Invitrogen, Carlsbad, CA). HPV16 E6 and E7 oncoproteins were overexpressed in bacte- ria as fusion proteins with glutathion-S-transferase at their N-terminus and the C-terminal undecapeptide of the SV40 large T-antigen at their C-terminus. Both systems have been described recently.29 The results of ELISA tests are expressed as the OD index which is the ratio between the OD and cut- off values.
Statistical Analysis
Total cumulative tobacco exposure and alcohol exposure were assessed as speciﬁed before.12 Continuous variables between groups were compared by the t-test. The chi-square test and in some instances the Fisher exact test were used to compare categorical variables between groups. Odds ratios (ORs) with 95% conﬁdence intervals (CI) were calculated in 2 3 2 tables using the EPI INFO statistical package (2002) and GraphPad InStat software (GraphPad Software, San Diego, CA). All tests were two-sided and the signiﬁcance level was 0.05. The corre- lation between variables and HPV positivity for HPV DNA and the presence of HPV-speciﬁc antibodies was assessed using logistic multivariate regression analysis with a forward stepwise procedure. Survival was measured in days from the date of diagnosis to the date of death or to the date the patient was last known to be alive. Patients who died of causes other than head and neck tumor were considered censored observa- tions in the disease-speciﬁc survival analyses. Time-to-event measures were analyzed by the Kaplan-Meier method, log- rank test, and Cox multivariate regression for proportional hazard. Ninety-ﬁve percent CI for ORs and hazard ratios (HRs) were based on normal approximation. Variables consid- ered in the Cox regression models were the presence of HR HPV in the tissue, age, tumor size (pT according to the TNM Classiﬁcation of the UICC, 1997), incidence, and extent of lymph node metastasis (pN according to the TNM Classiﬁca- tion of the UICC, 1997).
